WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:28.800
On screen text, a fusion of both worlds on two parallel worlds.

00:28.800 --> 00:35.560
Welcome back. This week we're going to go through using the Psoa lunging system

00:35.560 --> 00:41.240
to build better balance in the horses before we even get on. The reason why I

00:41.240 --> 00:46.200
like this system is because it works the whole body of the horse without the

00:46.200 --> 00:53.960
influence of the rider's positive or negative consequences. So here we have

00:53.960 --> 00:59.120
the setup of the Psoa. On the lowest setting we have the pulleys underneath

00:59.120 --> 01:05.120
attached to the girth, a pulley at the bit, a pulley low down and on the

01:05.120 --> 01:13.400
surcingle, and the fleece piece is right underneath the tail, below the hip, and

01:13.400 --> 01:19.600
above the hawk. Before you begin with the Psoa, your horse needs to have

01:19.600 --> 01:25.480
proficient lunging skills with a bridle and a halter and know all the commands

01:25.480 --> 01:32.680
that you are using to walk, trot, canter, slow down, speed up, close the circle and

01:32.680 --> 01:38.840
open the circle. After that point the horse can go in side reins as a one of

01:38.840 --> 01:43.600
two parts to build towards the Psoa lunging system. When you're teaching the

01:43.600 --> 01:47.560
horses to go in this system, make sure they're going forward so they don't get

01:47.560 --> 01:53.600
stuck and make your decisions very clear so that they know where you're going.

01:53.600 --> 02:00.400
Some common reactions to the Psoa is running through the pulley on the mouth

02:00.400 --> 02:06.120
so you'll see the horse's head come up and run forward and hit the bit really

02:06.120 --> 02:11.960
hard. That's a common reaction, just allow the horse to experience its own

02:11.960 --> 02:17.840
consequences for those reactions. Number two is they feel like they've been tied

02:17.840 --> 02:21.400
and they can't move, so sometimes you might have to lead the horse in front of

02:21.400 --> 02:26.720
you and lead them around like a little pony ride to indicate that they in fact

02:26.720 --> 02:31.280
can move but it's inside of a little box. You might want to loosen the Psoa a lot

02:31.280 --> 02:37.280
more if your horse is feeling more stuck. And then the third one, which is this

02:37.280 --> 02:42.280
example with this horse, is they scoot away from that bum fleece and they try

02:42.280 --> 02:49.840
to run and go faster to try and fix the feeling of the bum fleece making sure

02:49.840 --> 02:54.840
that their hind legs aren't sprawling out the back. So this is a very normal

02:54.840 --> 02:59.560
reaction as well and you'll see some of the corrections I make with this horse

02:59.560 --> 03:08.400
to help her understand that she can do that with her back legs. So it's very

03:08.400 --> 03:12.680
common for the horses to kick out at the back fleece as well and it's in a very

03:12.680 --> 03:19.600
safe place that it doesn't become, it doesn't slide up or down and it doesn't

03:19.600 --> 03:25.760
become misplaced. So if you're feeling like the Psoa is moving around while

03:25.800 --> 03:29.840
the horse is having these reactions, be sure to adjust it and move it to a

03:29.840 --> 03:34.560
safer place. If you're only feeling comfortable teaching your horse in the

03:34.560 --> 03:40.120
walk first, then moving to the trot, then moving to the canter, that's totally okay

03:40.120 --> 03:51.560
and sufficient for your level and the horse's level. Some great tips for horses

03:51.560 --> 03:55.280
that are scooting themselves away from the Psoa is to bring the circle in

03:55.280 --> 04:00.840
smaller. Keep the whip out, keep it active, keep the energy up so they don't move

04:00.840 --> 04:05.920
into getting stuck but that you're telling them that they can slow down and

04:05.920 --> 04:10.640
there's a space for them to step. Number two, if your horse is getting stuck and

04:10.640 --> 04:15.280
you're leading it around, you might have to do this in over the course of three

04:15.280 --> 04:18.720
days to build up to the canter and it might take you a little while to build

04:18.720 --> 04:23.120
up to the canter if they're very very much feeling stuck. If your horse is

04:23.120 --> 04:27.680
reactive by pulling on the bit, you may have to come under their bum with the

04:27.680 --> 04:32.720
whip and encourage them to go forward so that they can find the energy or find

04:32.720 --> 04:38.840
the space to go over their wither as opposed to scooting up and trying to run

04:38.840 --> 04:52.800
free from the bit. So after your horse is trained and ready for their lunging

04:52.800 --> 04:59.000
advancement to use the Psoa, you may start at walk and if your horse is

04:59.000 --> 05:05.800
sufficiently lessening, you may ask for transitions more promptly to get them

05:05.800 --> 05:11.360
more used to the boundaries which the Psoa is providing. These systems are

05:11.360 --> 05:15.960
super good for creating left and right balance and forward and back balance in

05:15.960 --> 05:23.040
the horse by engaging the loins at the top of the lower lumbar or in front of

05:23.040 --> 05:27.760
the hip area of the horse. This particular horse has a tendency to throw

05:27.760 --> 05:34.360
its hind legs out the back and evade good downward transitions so as expected

05:34.360 --> 05:39.760
in the Psoa in the lunge lesson that we're giving her, it's most difficult for

05:39.760 --> 05:44.200
her to do a downward transition since the Psoa will not allow her to sprawl

05:44.200 --> 05:48.600
her legs out the back so therefore she feels like she needs to keep going

05:48.600 --> 05:53.120
forward. Don't necessarily discipline your horse for this, let them experience

05:53.120 --> 05:58.920
the boundaries on their own and just simply make the circle smaller and allow

05:58.920 --> 06:04.040
them to learn on their own where their body is and how to control their own

06:04.040 --> 06:10.800
body. This connection is so important for the horses to learn. We can't always

06:10.800 --> 06:16.360
be able to see from the saddle unless we have someone videoing us of our effect

06:16.360 --> 06:22.080
on how we we teach the horses to do this with their bodies so lunging, groundwork,

06:22.080 --> 06:27.640
Psoa work can be so good for watching and seeing where your horse is accurate

06:27.640 --> 06:36.280
and where it's not. Partway through your lesson you will notice the horses

06:36.280 --> 06:41.120
intending to stretch way down, that's an excellent sign that means that they've

06:41.120 --> 06:45.480
been activating, they've been contracting their lower back muscles to push their

06:45.480 --> 06:50.200
back up and that means that you've done a great job. When you're first teaching

06:50.200 --> 06:54.840
the horses this make sure to keep the sessions short and attainable as this is

06:54.840 --> 06:58.880
quite an upgrade to fitness for each horse.

